[quote]ItÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s only a week into the Fantasia Film Festival, and I fear that the barrage of weird, wonderful, and occasionally psychotic films is causing cracks to form in my fragile psyche. Either IÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢m hallucinating, or I just watched a movie in which a computer-generated swamp-dragon defecates onto squealing Japanese women. 

Instant Swamp may also include water sprites that resemble sea-turtles filmed through a mescaline gel cap, and a robotic King Tut that predicts futures marriages. Directed by Adrift in TokyoÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s Satoshi Miki, itÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s the story of Haname (Kumiko Aso) a young woman searching to end her run of bad luck by digging up some childhood toys she dumped in a now non-existent swamp. Along the way, she finds her biological father Light Bulb, a hippie antique dealer played by a Japanese George Carlin, and develops a friendship with a punk rock electrician named Gas. 

While it embraces the same sense of joyful aimlessness as Adrift in Tokyo (read my review here), Instant Swamp is a much livelier film, primarily because Haname is sort of supercharged Hello Kitty when it comes to cuteness. That said, the humour in the film is a touch scattershot, which does make the story seem more like a trifle than a strong narrative. But for a lighthearted comedy, or a possible schizophrenic episode on my part, Instant Swamp definitely does the trick.[/quote] 

